"{\"uid\": \"metro.co.uk-2024-07-26-novak-djokovic-responds-trolls-whod-love-retire-olympics-21305298\", \"text\": \"Novak Djokovichas fired a message to the trolls who'd 'love' him to enter retirement after the Olympic tennis tournament atParis2024.  The 37-year-old GOAT is the figurehead of theBig Three eraof men's tennis, havingpassed Roger Federer and Rafael Nadal's tallyof major singles titles.  Federerhas retired, while Nadal has struggled with injuries in recent years, with the 38-year-old's Olympic singles participationin doubt over a thigh issue.  Djokovic, though, is still very much near the top of the sport - and came close to landing this year's Wimbledon title - only losing out toCarlos Alcarazin the final.  The Serbian won three of the four Grand Slam tournaments in 2023 and despite a dip in form this season, he is adamant he hasno plans to hang up his racketat all.  'I do not have retirement close in my mind, to be honest,' Djokovic said ahead of his Olympic singles first-round match against Australia's\\u00a0Matthew Ebden, and a potentialblockbuster second-round matchagainst Nadal, if the Spaniard is fit.  'Even though I know a lot of people would love me to retire so this era is done. But I think as long as there is at least one of us left competing, the era is still going.  'Of course there is a change of generations. You have Alcaraz and [Jannik] Sinner, currently they are our two best players in the world, deservedly.  'They are playing at a very high level particularly this year. They are very young and they are going to carry this sport in the future.  'But I have been present for the shift of many generations in the last 15 years and I like to see that.  Novak Djokovic also sent a classy message to British legend Andy Murray ahead of his retirement from professional tennis.  'I heard the news about Andy,' Djokovic said. 'I hope that he will have the best possible farewell in his last competitive match here in the Olympics. He's a legend of our sport. He's been an incredibly important player for tennis globally.  'Nadal of course, the same. Even more. All the results and achievements he's had particularly in this city, at Roland-Garros. Nadal still did not say when his last tournament will be so hopefully for the sake of the sport he can keep going.'  'I think it's also great that I am still able to play, Nadal, other veterans like [Stan] Wawrinka that have won multiple Grand Slams and made a big name in the sport.  'I think that also adds more significance and attention to our sport and I think it's a nice fine balance.  'Of course, the end is closer than the beginning, I know that, for me personally as well. But I still enjoy competition and I will keep going until I do not enjoy it anymore.'  ArrowMORE:What are Olympic medals made from? Gold, silver and bronze designs revealed  ArrowMORE:Paris Olympics Opening Ceremony: Parade of Nations order explained  ArrowMORE:British Olympic chief slams decision to allow Dutch rapist to compete  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy  Punchy analysis, transfer talk and more from Metro's football experts, sent straight to your inbox every week.  Let us know which team you support.Close  This site is protected by reCAPTCHA and theGoogle Privacy PolicyandTerms of Serviceapply. Your information will be used in line with ourPrivacy Policy\"}"